Text.label:
REVEAL FOR TIMEOUT LOGIC: 
Text is revealed immediately but
concealed again after a short 
duration of 160ms, unless
the Reveal button on the remote
is still held down, in which case
text continues to be revealed.  
The data command for Reveal is 
received every 100ms while the
Reveal button is held down.

"REVEAL FOR TIMEOUT" clears 
both flip flops. Then on the first 
timeout pulse after that, the first
flip flop is set (FIRST TIMEOUT),
then on the second timeout pulse,
the second flip flop is set (SECOND
TIMEOUT). At that point the NAND
gate gets a HIGH level and the 
concealed text is concealed again.
This two flip flop arrangement 
ensures that there has been at 
least 160ms since the last time the
REVEAL FOR TIMEOUT level was 
HIGH.

Flash counter is too slow in this 
simulation, so for testing, we'd need 
to add an OR gate and hard coded 
a constant to allow us to manually 
set the state.

Text.label:
0 = ODD FIELD
1 = EVEN FIELD

DBL HGT = /RC0 (i.e. Alternates)
NORMAL = CRS

NOTE: The Row Address value here for the display
read (i.e. not the CR reference read) is actually the 
Row Counter value plus 1. So the first value seen 
here is 0001. 

0001 = Blank line between characters. ROM output is inhibited for this value.
0010 = First row of pixels for a character
0011 = Second row of pixels for a character
0100 = Third row of pixels for a character
0101 = Fourth row of pixels for a character
0110 = Fifth row of pixels for a character
0111 = Sixth row of pixels for a character
1000 = Seventh row of pixels for a character
1001 = Eighth row of pixels for a character
1010 = Ninth (and final) row of pixels for a character
1011 = Row decoding also matches this to 9th row

0000 is not possible for the display read, but might be possible for 
character rounding reference read when the display read is 0001. It 
would be ignored though, as 0000 is not matched by anything 
in the ROM decoding.

The Mullard Technical Notes, Technical Communications, and patents all
suggest that the Odd field compares with the previous line, and the Even 
field compares with the next line, but this simulation suggests it is the other
way around with the SAA5050...  unless I've mistakenly reversed the CRS 
logic level somewhere, or what I think is Odd and Even is mistaken.

Text.label: DBL HEIGHT
/HOLD

6 bit Flash Counter. Counts from 0 to 63, i.e. 64 values. First
16 values, the flash is OFF, the other 48 values, the flash is ON.
Ratio is therefore 1:3 OFF/ON with a 0.7812Hz (50/64) frequency. 
Note that this is different from what the datasheet claims.

Text.label:
We subtract 1 from the Column value due to the way the counters work. Although the 
reset sets both counters to 0, the first CLK during the "display period" immediately increments 
it to 1, which means that the first active column value would be 1 without this subtraction. We 
need it to start at 0 to work with the LED Display components.
